      "content": "Originalism is often criticized as a tool for judges to advance their own political agendas by selectively interpreting historical context. Critics argue that originalists can cherry-pick historical evidence to support their preconceived notions, leading to biased and inconsistent rulings. They believe that this approach undermines the democratic process by allowing unelected judges to impose their views on society, rather than deferring to the will of the people as expressed through elected representatives. Originalists, however, counter that their method provides a more objective and principled basis for constitutional interpretation, preventing judges from imposing their personal values on the law. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether one prioritizes judicial restraint and adherence to the Constitution's original meaning, or democratic responsiveness and adaptability to contemporary issues.",
